1. How much data do you need to store? If you have limited storage space, you may want to delete records that are no longer needed to free up space.

2. How often do you need to access old records? If you need to access old records frequently, it may be better to keep them in the database.

3. Are there any compliance or legal requirements to store the data for a certain period of time? If yes, you may need to keep the records in the database for a specified period of time.

4. Are there any performance considerations? Keeping too much data in the database can affect read and write performance.

In general, it's a good practice to delete records that are no longer needed to keep the database clean and performant. One way to handle this is to set an expiration time on each SMPP segment record in MongoDB, just like you would do in Redis. Once a record has expired, it can be deleted automatically by MongoDB.

